        "content": "<p>I have a per peeve with negation.<br>\nWe write neither parentheses nor spaces around the (prefix) negation operator.<br>\nIt can look like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"bp\">¬</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊂</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>From technical perspective, there is nothing wrong with it; it is unambiguous and concise.<br>\nUnfortunately, it confuses my brain.<br>\nI almost never read it correctly on the first try.<br>\nTo me, it looks like \"some operation applied to A gives a strict subset of B\".<br>\nAm I the only one?<br>\nDo we want to change it?<br>\nTwo possible alternatives are:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"bp\">¬</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊂</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">¬</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊂</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Changing it would mean both changing the declaration of the notation or its delaborator, and refactoring Std and Mathlib to the new convention.</p>",
        "id": 492519703,
        "sender_full_name": "Martin Dvořák",
        "timestamp": 1736347638
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>perhaps we should just use <code>⊄</code> for this?</p>",
        "id": 492521194,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1736348037
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think we should create a crossed version of all infix operators.</p>",
        "id": 492521330,
        "sender_full_name": "Martin Dvořák",
        "timestamp": 1736348067
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>does that also restrict to those with result type <code>Bool</code> or <code>Prop</code>? (in typical use case)</p>",
        "id": 492522479,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1736348392
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you want to suggest that we should create a negated version for all relational infix operators?<br>\nI think <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110038\">@Kevin Buzzard</span> had a similar suggestion in the past.</p>",
        "id": 492523187,
        "sender_full_name": "Martin Dvořák",
        "timestamp": 1736348578
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i don't remember having an issue with negation in general but I do remember having a pet peeve with <code>¬ x ∈ S</code> years ago and the upshot being that we now have <code>x ∉ S</code></p>",
        "id": 492523594,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1736348698
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>possibly... ideally, these are just notation/pretty print things i think (e.g. i don't like how <code>≠</code> gets simped to <code>¬A = B</code> (or why these even are separate things))</p>",
        "id": 492523755,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1736348748
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>even if we are not going to  add this new symbol, i do agree that <code>¬A ⊂ B</code> is too easily read <code>(¬A) ⊂ B</code>, and indeed prefer <code>¬(A ⊂ B)</code></p>",
        "id": 492525674,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1736349372
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>similar for <code>⊆</code>, all those other set notations</p>",
